A Federal High Court in Lagos on Wednesday sentenced a 28-year-old man, Basit Akangbe, to six months imprisonment for trafficking in 400g of cannabis sativa. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the National Drug Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA) arraigned Akangbe on a count charge of drug trafficking. He pleaded guilty and begged for leniency. He said that he would become a better person. Reviewing the facts of the case, the prosecutor, Mr Jeremiah Aernan, tendered documents in evidence, urged the court to convict Akangbe. Aernan tendered in evidence, a written statement of the defendant, a drug analysis form, a request for scientific aid form and a remnant of the banned substance. The court admitted the documents and marked them as exhibits. Delivering judgment, Justice Chukwujekwu Aneke found Akangbe guilty as charged, and convicted him. He held that Akangbe’s sentence should take effect from the day of his arrest. The judge, however, gave the convict an option to pay N20,000 fine. The prosecutor had earlier told the court that Akangbe committed the offence on Dec. 5, 2019. He said the defendant was arrested at Kewe Bus Stop in Ejigbo, Lagos State, while engaging in the sale of cannabis sativa weighing 400g. According to the NDLEA, trafficking in cannabis, cocaine, heroin or other narcotics contravenes the provisions of Section 11(c) of the NDLEA Act, 2004 (NAN) 